At 5 weeks old Hadley was diagnosed with Hypertrophic Cardiomyopathy, the same condition that her dad has along with his sister (her aunt who she never got to meet), who passed at the age of 22 from the condition.  Hypertrophic Cardiomyopathy is a disease in which the heart muscle becomes thickened.  If it gets too thick it can make it harder for the heart to pump blood and you can go into sudden cardiac arrest. Many people have this condition without knowing it, some can go through life without ever needing any surgery or medicine, and others are not as lucky.  No two conditions are the same, how and when it shows up and other areas that become affected are all unique.  Hadley has seen the Heart Failure Team at Children’s Mercy every 2-3 months since she was 5 weeks old. 

In September 2020 they were told that her condition has progressed and she needed a Myectomy and possibly a valve transplant.  January 28th, 2021, just three days before her 3rd birthday she had open heart surgery.  The surgery was a complete success and they were able to remove the thickening of the heart wall without compromising the valve, they were in shock and incredibly thankful.  They knew there was a chance that she would need another Myetcomy or additional surgery later on but truly only had positive thoughts and definitely thought they had more time.  In July of 2022 at her usual scan that they have every 2-3 months, they got hit with the news.  Not only has her condition progressed again but now the mitral valve threw a huge wrench in the plan.  Another Myectomy was no longer a possibility and the only way to save her life was if she received a new heart.  On September 14th, 2022 Hadley officially joined the Heart Transplant List.  She will be 5 on January 31st, 2023 and now this family just waits. They are on call 24/7 for the phone call that says they have found a heart. 

Please keep this sweet family in your thoughts and prayers.

I’ve had an editing queue non-stop since last January. It felt like the never ending list. The list that went on and on and on. The list that left me emotionally torn at times. The list that’s left my eye balls bloodshot and burning from staring at the screen for hours on end and growing what appears to be a hunchback from poor posture while shooting and editing too. The list I can complain about but with love and appreciation because it signifies the amount of families that put their trust in me to create an invaluable gift. The list that supports my family and keeps this business of mine thriving beyond my wildest dreams. The list that allows me to express myself creatively and do what I absolutely love. So thank you to those names on my list this year. Thank you for being a special part of my story. The bed is a staple set I use during my intimate maternity sessions. There are endless posing opportunities using a bed. Here is a list of some of my go-to favorites..

• Lay center on the bed, head closest to camera. 
• Criss cross apple sauce in the center of the bed.
• Sit on the corner end of the bed with legs extended 
• Kneel on the bed with knees positioned diagonally toward the light. 
• Sit front and center on the floor, lean shoulders against the bed, arch back, and legs extend out in front. 

Like and save to reference prior to your next studio maternity session!

It’s true, newborn sessions are unique in that they are best within the first few weeks of life. However, my favorite time to photograph a newborn session is during weeks 2-3. Yep, not the first week of life. 

It’s common for newborns to lose 5-10% of their body weight after birth. By 14-21 days old they’ve gained weight and have more defined baby features. 

In weeks 2-3 newborns are still sleepy but have moments of alertness to capture open eye contact shots which adds striking baby headshots and variety within their gallery collection. 

In weeks 2-3 newborns are still flexible enough to be wrapped but they also enjoy freedom to kick and stretch which is movement I love to capture that brings life to their photos.

Birth leaves us mamas in lingering pain and exhaustion weeks to follow. We need that first week to rest and heal from our birthing experience. Respecting your family and allowing you time to bond and get acclimated to life with a new little love is important. 

After lockdown, I returned to the studio and photographed 3-8 week old newborn babies and absolutely fell in love. I discovered my sweet spot of 2-3 weeks. 

Mamas, erase the idea of one week being best. Trust me. I’ve had nearly a decade of experience and I’ll confidently take care of your baby regardless of age, I promise.

4 FAQs

• Is your arch real or a backdrop?
• Is your brick wall real or faux brick panels?
• What type of white floors do you have?
• Do you only use natural or artificial light? 

The short answer for all of the above: it’s all the real deal. 

I hired a professional to create a custom build out of my arch to hold space for my bed set. The beauty of a real arch over a faux back drop is you can shoot at any angle and see genuine shadows created by the depth of the arch. Also, the unique texture and color I chose for my arch make it one of a kind to me and my space. 

The brick is original historic brick as the River Market building was built in 1925. At some point it was white washed but now is weathered and shows natural signs of distress which bring beauty and character to the space. 

The floors are painted concrete. This was a scary change for me but I absolutely love it. Yes it’s a pain to keep clean and free from chipping but it was a risk I was willing to make. We color matched the brick to the paint color for the floor and arch to create a cohesive look for the space. 

I only use natural light. In my studio I have two large 32-lite black gridded windows on the second floor of the building. Both windows are west facing and diffused with custom ordered linen curtains. 

I hope this information is helpful. Please do your research prior to executing any project for your own space. Let me know if you have any further questions!

How do I get siblings to cooperate during their newborn photography session? Trust. When trust exists, a friendship grows and flourishes. Warmly befriend them. You’re more than likely a complete stranger to this child. You must earn their trust. Introduce yourself. Get down on their level and talk with them not at them. Give them a tour of your studio space. Make them feel comfortable and safe to be themselves. Be attentive to their needs and wants. Seek opportunities to chat with them and make them feel special. Engage in activities with them. Ask them to be your helper or assistant when they aren’t in the photo. Give them positive reinforcement when they are doing something right. Praise them. Show your appreciation when they follow directions. Have fun! It takes action to build trust. Once you earn their trust they are more willing to happily participate in family photos.
